properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High concentrations of pollutants trigger a poor air quality this morning, especially in locales where the emissions of pollutants are more significant. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. In Quebec, wood heating is the main source of fine particles that contribute to smog during winter. This activity generates the largest number of these particulates, more than industrial activities and transportation. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canadas website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministre de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montral, visit the Rseau de surveillance de la qualit de lair de la Ville de Montrals website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Qubec, visit the Ministre de la Sant et des Services sociauxs website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction rgionale de sant publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-lle-de-Montral at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2021-01-20T22:59:55-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential winter storm beginning Thursday evening. Total estimated snowfall: likely exceeding 15 cm. Maximum wind gusts: northerly near 70 km/h. Locations: the northeast coast from Clarenville to Green Bay - White Bay, excluding the Bonavista peninsula. Time span: Thursday evening into Friday afternoon. Remarks: A storm is expected to form south of Nova Scotia on Wednesday and track east of Newfoundland Thursday and Friday. Snow is expected to spread across the northeast coast Thursday evening, accompanied by strong winds and areas of blowing snow. Conditions will improve by Friday afternoon. There is still uncertainty regarding the track of this storm, which will have a significant impact on snowfall amounts. Should the storm pass further east, snowfall amounts will be much less, while if it tracks closer to the island, higher accumulations will be expected. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2021-01-21T11:20:51-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2021-01-20T19:21:51-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2331399400.2021
Area: Grand Falls-Windsor and vicinity, Bay of Exploits, Bonavista North, Clarenville and vicinity, Gander and vicinity, Green Bay - White Bay, Terra Nova

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Total snowfall: 20 to 35 cm. Maximum wind gusts: northeasterly 80 km/h. Locations: Avalon and Bonavista Peninsulas. Time span: near noon Thursday until early Friday morning. Remarks: Snow at times heavy will begin over the southern Avalon Peninsula near noon Thursday then elsewhere in the afternoon or evening. Strong northeasterly winds will accompany the snow. Conditions are expected to improve Thursday night over the southern Avalon and elsewhere by Friday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly near 80 km/h. Locations: Coastal Labrador from Lodge Bay to Rigolet. Time span: ending this evening. Remarks: Fresh snowfall will combine with strengthening northwesterly winds this morning to produce poor visibility in blowing snow, particularly over exposed areas. Conditions will improve as the winds and snow ease tonight. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
